elements.content: The coordination polymers (CPs) of bis­(3-pyridyl-acrylamido)­ethane (L) with nitrate, acetate, and perchlorate salts of Cu­(II), Cd­(II), and Zn­(II) were synthesized, and their crystal structures have been analyzed with respect to the influence of anions, hydrogen bonding, and their solid state [2 + 2] photochemical reactivity. Four out of the six CPs (1–4) containing NO3 – and AcO– ions were found to form one-dimensional chains and exhibit solid state [2 + 2] reactivity. Two CPs (5–6) containing ClO4 – ions were found to form ML 2 discrete complexes which are photostable. The CPs 1 and 4 were found to form single [2 + 2] dimers, while 2 and 3 resulted in the formation of polymers via solid state [2 + 2] polymerization upon irradiation. The photoproducts are characterized by 1H NMR, electrospray ionization mass spectrometry, and matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization–time of flight (MALDI-TOF) spectra. The dimer was charecterized by single crystal X-ray structure determination. The MALDI-TOF analyses of polymers indicate the highest degree (29-mer) of polymerization.

Introduction

Hitherto, a vast number of coordination polymers (CPs) have been synthesized using bis-pyridyl ligands owing to their diversities in structural topologies and pre-eminent applications in luminescence, catalysis, gas storage, and magnetism. The bis-pyridyl ligands containing amide moieties are of interest to us given their ability to form hydrogen bonds and enhance the dimensionalities of networks. We and others have shown that such ligands form CPs with novel topologies, and the spacers between the amido pyridine moieties and anions play a major role in dictating topologies of CPs and hydrogen bonding. One of the current interests in CPs is their utility to template [2 + 2] reactions to form cyclobutane containing dimers or polymers. Recently, we have introduced olefin moieties into these bis amidopyridine containing ligands to study the possibility of templating solid state [2 + 2] reactions in their CPs. The Ag(I)-CPs of olefin containing ligands have been well exploited for such templation of solid state [2 + 2] reactions as they have a tendency to form argentophilic interactions. In particular, we have shown that the ligand L with the ethyl spacer is unreactive in organic crystal but reactive in their Ag(I)-coordination polymers to yield a crystalline coordination polymer of organic polymer (CPOP). The derivative of L, that is, containing a butyl in place of an ethyl spacer, was reactive in both organic crystal as well as in its Ag(I)-CP to form crystalline materials of OPs and CPOPs, respectively.

elements.content: In the crystals of organic as well as in their Ag­(I)-CPs of these molecules, the common feature is the well-defined two-dimensional (2D) hydrogen bonding layer that is formed through amide-to-amide hydrogen bonds. The single-crystal-to-single-crystal (SCSC) reactions in both these materials have been attributed to the shock absorbing nature of hydrogen bonding layers as they remain intact before and after the reaction. In order to investigate further, the CPs of L () with other metals such as Cu­(II), Zn­(II), and Cd­(II) are prepared in the presence of nitrate, acetate, and perchlorate anions. These anions were shown by us earlier to interfere in amide-to-amide hydrogen bonds. These CPs are of importance as they are expected to form CPs, which do not associate through amide-to-amide hydrogen bonds due to the interference of anions and therefore provide an opportunity of evaluation of the role of amide-to-amide bonding layers in the templation of SCSC solid state [2 + 2] polymerization reactions. Recently, we have also shown that triply intertwined one-dimensional (1D) helical CPs of Cd­(II) and Cu­(II) also do not contain amide-to-amide hydrogen bonds but undergo photopolymerization reactions.

Results and Discussion

The complexation reactions were carried out by direct mixing alcoholic solutions of L and corresponding metal salts. The single crystals of complex, {[Cu3(L)3(NO3)2(H2O)10]⋅4(NO3)⋅4(H2O)} n , 1 are prepared by reacting Cu(NO3)2 with L in MeOH/CH2Cl2 (2:1 ratio) and water. The single crystals of complex, {[Cu(L)(H2O)(CH3COO)2](H2O)} n , 4 are obtained by reacting aqueous solution of Cu(CH3COO)2 with EtOH/CHCl3 (2:1 ratio) solution of L, whereas the crystals of complexes, {[Cd(L)2(H2O)4]⋅4(H2O)⋅2(ClO4)} n , 5 and {[Zn(L)2(H2O)4]⋅4(H2O)⋅2(ClO4)} n , 6 are produced by reacting L and corresponding metal salts in EtOH-CHCl3 (2:1 ratio).

In the complex 1, the asymmetric unit is constituted by two symmetry independent Cu­(II) and ligands (one with full occupancy and another with half occupancy), three anions, and five coordinated and two free water molecules. The Cu­(II) centers adopt octahedral geometry with two each of pyridine units and water molecules at the equatorial positions. The two Cu­(II) centers differ in their axial coordination: the Cu­(II) with full occupancy contains one each of water (Cu–Ow: 2.295 Å) and nitrate ions (Cu–O: 2.584 Å) in axial position and the Cu­(II) with half occupancy contains water molecules (Cu–Ow: 2.007 Å). Both the Cu­(II) centers propagate 1D chains (a,b) that are assembled through hydrogen bonds between H2O molecules, anions, and amide moieties (c). The CO groups of amides hydrogen bonded with coordinated water molecules (O···O: 2.688, 2.693, 2.764, and 2.795 Å), while N–H of amides are hydrogen bonded with nitrate ions ((N···O, N–H···O: 2.903 Å, 160°). Such hydrogen bonding resulted in the reactive orientation of double bonds of three successive molecules with a distance between double bonds of 3.75 Å. The fourth successive molecule exhibits a double bond distance of 4.66 Å, making it unreactive and suggesting that the irradiation of the crystals may lead to the formation of trimers (d).

elements.content: The crystal structure analysis of CPs indicated that 1–4 containing nitrate and acetate have reactive alignment of double bonds for [2 + 2] photochemical reaction. Therefore, the solid state reactivity of these materials was investigated by irradiating the crystals under sunlight. The crystal structures analyses suggested that 1 should form a trimer, 2 and 3 should form polymers, and 4 should form a dimer. All these materials indeed were found to be photoreactive with the loss of single crystalline nature. Similarly, the complexes 5 and 6 were found to be unreactive as suggested by their crystal structures. The products were characterized by 1H NMR, electrospray ionization mass spectrometry (ESI-MS)/matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization–time of flight (MALDI-TOF), single crystal X-ray diffraction.

elements.content: The ligand L was shown to form four 1D coordination polymers and two coordination complexes. The presence of flat anions such as nitrate and acetate resulted in the formation 1D chains (1–4), whereas the presence of tetrahedral anion-like perchlorate resulted in the formation of discrete complexes (5 and 6). Unlike in Ag­(I)-1D chains which were reported by us earlier, the hydrogen bonding 2D layers of L were not observed in these complexes. The amide-to-amide hydrogen bonding is disturbed by anions and the presence of water molecules. However, the 1D chains were found to have required reactive alignment in the CPs of 1–4 making them photoreactive but not in an SCSC manner. These materials exemplify the essence of well-defined hydrogen bonding for the reactions to occur in an SCSC manner. We note here that the polymers obtained from 2 and 3 are of the highest degree polymerization [2 + 2] reactions to date (29-mer). Our recently reported example using a different ligand was found to have 21-mer. In those examples, the triple intertwining of the 1D chains make the reactions SCSC, although they do not contain 2D hydrogen bonding layers. These studies further emphasize the importance of CPs in templating solid state [2 + 2] polymerization/dimerization reactions. The crystal structure of the dimer (7) was found to show puckered geometry for cyclobutane moiety and interesting hydrogen bonding patterns.

Conclusions

The ligand L was shown to form four 1D coordination polymers and two coordination complexes. The presence of flat anions such as nitrate and acetate resulted in the formation 1D chains (1-4), whereas the presence of tetrahedral anion-like perchlorate resulted in the formation of discrete complexes (5 and 6). Unlike in Ag(I)-1D chains which were reported by us earlier, the hydrogen bonding 2D layers of L were not observed in these complexes. The amide-to-amide hydrogen bonding is disturbed by anions and the presence of water molecules. However, the 1D chains were found to have required reactive alignment in the CPs of 1-4 making them photoreactive but not in an SCSC manner. These materials exemplify the essence of well-defined hydrogen bonding for the reactions to occur in an SCSC manner. We note here that the polymers obtained from 2 and 3 are of the highest degree polymerization [2 + 2] reactions to date (29-mer). Our recently reported example using a different ligand was found to have 21-mer. In those examples, the triple intertwining of the 1D chains make the reactions SCSC, although they do not contain 2D hydrogen bonding layers. These studies further emphasize the importance of CPs in templating solid state [2 + 2] polymerization/dimerization reactions. The crystal structure of the dimer (7) was found to show puckered geometry for cyclobutane moiety and interesting hydrogen bonding patterns.

The structures were solved by direct methods and refined by least-squares methods on F2 using SHELX-2014. Non-hydrogen atoms were refined anisotropically, and hydrogen atoms were fixed at calculated positions and refined using a riding model.
